Flames shot from Thassalin's mouth as the huge Thraki set a specific piece of forest on fire and then circled over it to detect movements. Strangely, the eerie screeching behind him ceased as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What is this, Tenuk, you have already turned into a Thraki before!"
"If I fly myself, it's entirely different than being suddenly lifted up by a huge pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not in agreement with Nyssi. He looked less black than usual and his claws had dug so deep into Thassalin's back that the Thraki bled. Thassalin apparently didn't care about this. Nevertheless, he had realized that he had scared his new friends and landed in a clearing.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I SMELLED SOMETHING. I HAD TO DEAL WITH IT!"
"But did you have to drag us along too?" growled Tenuk as he climbed down from Thassalin's back and slid down his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We've abandoned our big, strong fighter! How is he supposed to catch up with us?"
"He'll think of something..." growled Nyssi. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not dumb."
"True, but can Retvik drive?"
Nyssi winked and turned back to Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't seen him drive a nice little car like Kayel's either. Besides, he only started taking the car for work because you always drive us. He only has his bicycle."
Loud laughter interrupted her. Thassalin suddenly found something incredibly funny, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took a bit too long for Thassalin to calm down.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I IMAGINED YOUR GIANT FRIEND ARMORED UP ON SUCH A TINY LITTLE BIKE FOR TEMTHAN KIDS. THAT WAS HILARIOUS! I WISH I HAD SOME KIND OF TELEPATHY. A BEAUTIFUL IMAGINATION! ONE I CAN'T SHARE!"
Kayel chuckled, as he could imagine what was going on in Thassalin's mind. "Yeah, that's true. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off?"
Thassalin grunted, took off, and disappeared. When he returned shortly after, he threw something lifeless in front of Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, gold-white draconic creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR SCREAMS. SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The mighty Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel froze as well and looked intently at a gap in the clearing. Something large and black stared at them and hissed. Whatever it was, it spread out two enormous pairs of wings and shot toward Thassalin, without caring about the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk just barely managed to take cover, but Nyssi was dragged along and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling him onto his back with his incredibly long, skillful tail before he himself launched into the air. The black, double-winged creature pursued them at high speed.
Kayel snapped angrily as he took his rifle from his back and opened a bag containing a belt of ammunition. He slung the belt over his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?" asked Kayel.
"You want to follow them?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... One of them is a huge monster!"
"So what? I'm standing here with a top-notch rifle in my hand and could shoot right away. But, well, how should I say – I would have to be able to see it in order to hit it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to make more room. With a soft, painful grunt, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turned into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, light-blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Get on."
Like an otherwise ordinary-looking Thraki, Tenuk now had a proper scale armor running along his back. Fortunately, he had also grown a pair of spines on his back, which Kayel could use to hold on. It took a little too long for Tenuk to get the flight started, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to catch up.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up beneath them, and Tenuk could only barely avoid a collision.
"That's probably the other terrifying giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel furrowed his brow. He tried to shoot at the second creature, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too focused on flying toward Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other creature was pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to keep the monster in sight. The fact that it was following them was an advantage for Kayel, as it made it easier for him to aim and fire. Two shots went through the upper wings of the creature. It screamed in pain and sank back under the trees. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but it definitely wouldn't be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead of them, Nyssi desperately clung on while Thassalin flailed around and spat fireballs at the blackened monster. The creature was definitely injured. It seemed extremely angry, but not ready to give up. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her own weapon, a good old shot gun. It wasn't exactly the first choice, but maybe the buckshot would scare off the black creature.
